{We follow the games of Christiansen and Karpov.  Jan van Reek} 1. d4 d5 2. c4
e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd3 Nbd7 8. Nge2 Re8 9. Qc2
Nf8 10. h3 c6 11. g4 {
Christiansen is not intimidated by his opponent and plays his own game.} Bd7
12. O-O-O Rc8 13. Kb1 b5 14. Nf4 $1 a5 15. Bf5 a4 {
Both sides advance towards the hostile king.} 16. Nd3 Bxf5 $5 17. gxf5 N8d7 $2
(17... Ne4 $1 18. Bxe7 Nxc3+ 19. Qxc3 Qxe7 {
makes useful exchanges for the defender.}) 18. Rhg1 Bf8 19. Rg2 c5 $6 ({
Preferable is} 19... Kh8 20. Rdg1 a3) 20. dxc5 Nxc5 21. Nxc5 Rxc5 22. Qd3 Kh8
$6 (22... b4 $5 {counterattacks.}) 23. Ne4 $1 {
A brilliant combination decides the game.} Rxe4 24. Qxe4 Qc8 25. Qd3 Ne4 26. f3
Nxg5 27. Rxg5 Be7 28. f6 $1 Bxf6 29. Rxd5 h6 30. Rxc5 Qxc5 31. Rc1 {
It looked like Spassky handled the white pieces with such verve.} 1-0

